The '''Michigan State Spartans''' are the [[sport|athletic]] teams that represent [[Michigan State University]]. The school's athletic program includes 23 [[Varsity team|varsity]] sports teams. Their mascot is a [[Spartan Army|Spartan]] warrior named [[Sparty]], and the school colors are green and white. The university participates in the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]]'s Division I-A and in the [[Big Ten Conference]] in all Varsity sports except ice hockey, which competes in the [[Central Collegiate Hockey Association]]. Michigan State offers 11 varsity sports for men and 12 for women.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://msuspartans.cstv.com/trads/msu-trads-mascot.html|title=Meet Sparty--Our Celebrity Mascot |publisher=MSU Spartans }}</ref>

The university's athletic director is Mark Hollis, who was promoted to the position on [[January 1]], [[2008]].<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/2007-09-12-3746318224_x.htm|title=Michigan State promotes Mark Hollis to athletic director|publisher=[[USA Today]]}}</ref> Hollis replaced [[Ron Mason]], who served as head hockey coach from 1979 to 2002, retiring with a 608&ndash;261&ndash;64 record at MSU.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://msuspartans.cstv.com/sports/m-hockey/mtt/mason_ron00.html|title=Ron Mason|publisher=MSU Spartans}}</ref>

MSU's [[American football|football]] team has won or shared six national championships in 1951, 1952, 1955, 1957, 1965, and 1966, and has won the [[Rose Bowl Game|Rose Bowl]] in 1954, 1956, and 1988.<ref name="info" /> Its men's basketball team won the [[NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship|NCAA National Championship]] in 1979 and 2000.<ref name="info" /> The MSU men's [[ice hockey]] has won [[NCAA Men's Ice Hockey Championship|national titles]] in 1966, 1986, and 2007.<ref name="info" /> MSU's golf team won the Big Ten Championship in 1969 and again in 2005.<ref name="info">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.myspartans.info/|title=  My Spartan Info  |publisher=My Spartans }}</ref>

==History==
In 1925, the institution changed its names to ''Michigan State College of Agriculture and Applied Science'', and as an agricultural school, its teams were referred to as the Aggies. Looking to move beyond its agricultural roots, Michigan State held a contest to find a new nickname. They decided to call the teams the "Michigan Staters". Local sports writers for the [[Lansing State Journal]] and the Capital News went through the losing entries to find a shorter and more heroic name. They decided on the "[[Spartan Army|Spartans]]". By coincidence, Justin Morrill had once compared the Land Grant colleges to the schools of ancient Sparta. With a heroic name and a historic precedent, the "Spartans" quickly caught on as the teams' new nickname. Within a few years, the College changed the lyrics of the [[Michigan State University Fight Song|Fight Song]] to reflect the name change of the College and its sports teams.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-04-17|url=http://newsroom.msu.edu/snav/184/page.htm|title=MSU Facts |publisher=[[Michigan State University]] }}</ref>

