As the college grew in size, it looked to join a major collegiate conference. When the [[University of Chicago]] eliminated varsity [[football]] and withdrew from the Western Conference (now the [[Big Ten Conference|Big Ten]]) in 1946, Michigan State president [[John A. Hannah]] lobbied hard to take its place. The Big Ten finally admitted M.S.C. in 1949.<ref name="sports history" /> After joining the conference, head [[American football|football]] coach [[Biggie Munn|Clarence L. "Biggie" Munn]] led the Spartan football team to the [[Rose Bowl Game|Rose Bowl]] in the 1953<U+2013>54 season, beating [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]] 28&ndash;20.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/bowls/yearly_results.php?year=1953|title=1953 Season Bowl Games|publisher=College Football Data Warehouse}}</ref> Successor coach [[Duffy Daugherty|Hugh "Duffy" Daugherty]] carried the football team to a second Rose Bowl where it again defeated UCLA, 17&ndash;14.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/bowls/yearly_results.php?year=1955|title=1955 Season Bowl Games|publisher=College Football Data Warehouse}}</ref>
[[Image:MSU Spartan Stadium Facade.jpg|thumb|200px|right|[[Spartan Stadium, East Lansing|Spartan Stadium]] hosts varsity [[American football|football]] games and other events.]]

In more recent years, Michigan State's successes and failures in the [[Final Four]] have resulted in clashes involving the police in 1997,<ref>{{cite news|title=E.L. turmoil angers city|author=Terlep, Sharon|publisher=[[The State News]]|date=1997-09-09}}</ref> 1998,<ref>{{cite news|author=Mullin, Greg|title=17 arrested in weekend riot|publisher=[[The State News]]|date=1998-05-04}}</ref> and 1999.<ref>{{cite news|title=Thousands of revelers crowd streets in violent, fiery riot|publisher=[[The State News]]|date=1999-03-28}}</ref> Local and national news referred to the disturbances as riots. After several years without any major incidents, another disturbance broke out on [[April 2, 2005]] after the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill|North Carolina]]'s men's basketball team defeated MSU in the 2005 [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[Final Four]].<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.statenews.com/index.php/article/2005/04/police_student_actions|author=Phillips, Lauren|title=Police, student actions disputed|publisher=[[The State News]]|date=2005-04-04}}</ref> Officially called a "civil disturbance," the ensuing violence sparked accusations of [[police brutality]] in East Lansing.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.cityofeastlansing.com/CITYGOV/SAFETY/POLICE/PostGameEvents/agendaminutes/082205m.pdf|title=City of East Lansing Review Commission Minutes}}</ref>

==Varsity sports==
Michigan State has 23 [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] Division I-A [[Varsity team|varsity]] teams: 11 varsity sports for men and 12 for women. They participate in the [[Big Ten Conference]] in all sports except ice hockey, which competes in the [[Central Collegiate Hockey Association]].<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://ccha.cstv.com/sports/m-hockey/spec-rel/hockey-day-in-mich.html|title='Hockey Day' in Michigan Set for February |publisher=[[CCHA]] }}</ref>

