MSU's men's basketball team has won the [[NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship|National Championship]] twice: in 1979 and 2000.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/s/2000/1106/861084.html|title=Spartans can relate to Izzo's winning ways|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> In 1979, [[Magic Johnson|Earvin "Magic" Johnson]],<ref name="magicjohnson">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/j/johnsma02.html|title=Magic Johnson Statistics|publisher=Basketball Reference}}</ref> along with [[Greg Kelser]],<ref name="gregkelser">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/k/kelsegr01.html|title=Greg Kelser Statistics|publisher=Basketball Reference}}</ref> [[Jay Vincent]],<ref name="jayvincent">{{cite web|accessdate=2008|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/v/vinceja01.html|title=Jay Vincent Statistics|publisher=Basketball Reference}}</ref> and Mike Brkovich, carried the MSU team to a 75&ndash;64 win against the [[Larry Bird]]-led [[Indiana State University|Indiana State]] Sycamores. In 2000, three players from [[Flint, Michigan]], [[Morris Peterson]],<ref name="morrispeterson">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/p/petermo01.html|title=Morris Peterson Statistics|publisher=Basketball Reference}}</ref> [[Charlie Bell (basketball)|Charlie Bell]],<ref name="charliebell">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/b/bellch01.html|title=Charlie Bell Statistics|publisher=Basketball Reference}}</ref> and [[Mateen Cleaves]]<ref name="mateencleaves">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/c/cleavma01.html|title=Mateen Cleaves Statistics|publisher=Basketball Reference}}</ref> carried the team to its second national title. Dubbed the "Flintstones", they were the key to the Spartans' win against the [[University of Florida]].<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A17213-2005Mar31.html|title=Five Spartans Form New 'Flintstones' |publisher=[[Washington Post]]|date=2005-04-01|author=Schlabach, Mark  }}</ref>

On [[December 13]], [[2003]], Michigan State and [[University of Kentucky|Kentucky]] played at the most-attended basketball game in history, when they played a match in front of 78,130 at [[Ford Field]], a stadium in [[Detroit]]. Kentucky won 79&ndash;74.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://msuspartans.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/recaps/121303aaa.html|title=Men's Basketball Falls To No. 8 Kentucky|publisher=MSU Spartans}}</ref> Since 1995, Michigan has been coached by [[Tom Izzo]], who has a 300&ndash;120 record.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://msuspartans.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/mtt/izzo_tom00.html|publisher=MSU Spartans|title=Player Bio: Tom Izzo}}</ref> Izzo's coaching helped the team make four of nine NCAA [[Final Four]]s from 1999 to 2007, winning the title in 2000.
Michigan State basketball has been selected for ten consecutive NCAA tournament bids from 1998 to 2007, making four final fours during that span.  Overall, Michigan State has made it to the final four six times and has made 23 NCAA Tournament appearances.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/columns/story?columnist=katz_andy&id=2862538|title=Spartans' performance stacks up against anyone's |publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=2007-05-07|author=Katz, Andy  }}</ref>

Spartans formerly or currently in the [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] include [[Earvin "Magic" Johnson]],<ref name="magicjohnson"/> [[Greg Kelser]],<ref name="gregkelser"/> [[Jay Vincent]],<ref name="jayvincent"/> [[Steve Smith (basketball)|Steve Smith]],<ref name="stevesmith">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/s/smithst01.html|title=Steve Smith Statistics|publisher=Basketball Reference}}</ref> [[Scott Skiles]],<ref name="scottskiles">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/s/skilesc01.html|title=Scott Skiles Statistics|publisher=Basketball Reference}}</ref> [[Jason Richardson]],<ref name="jasonrichardson">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/r/richaja01.html|title=Jason Richardson Statistics|publisher=Basketball Reference}}</ref> [[Mateen Cleaves]],<ref name="mateencleaves"/> [[Alan Anderson]],<ref name="alanderson">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/a/anderal01.html|title=Alan Anderson Statistics|publisher=Basketball Reference}}</ref> [[Zach Randolph]],<ref name="zachrandolph">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/r/randoza01.html|title=Zach Randolph Statistics|publisher=Basketball Reference}}</ref> [[Morris Peterson]],<ref name="morrispeterson"/> [[Eric Snow]],<ref name="ericsnow">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.basketball-reference.com/players/s/snower01.html|title=Eric Snow Statistics|publisher=Basketball Reference}}</ref> and [[Charlie Bell (basketball)|Charlie Bell]].<ref name="charliebell"/>

MSU also has a women's basketball team. [[Suzy Merchant]] took over as head coach in 2007,<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://msuspartans.cstv.com/sports/w-baskbl/spec-rel/043007aaa.html|title=Suzy Merchant Named Spartan Women's Basketball Coach|publisher=MSU Spartans}}</ref> and replaced [[Joanne P. McCallie]] who left MSU to coach for [[Duke University]]. Before coming to Michigan State, Merchant spent nine years as head coach of [[Eastern Michigan University]]'s team, where she won the most games in the school's history.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://msuspartans.cstv.com/sports/w-baskbl/mtt/merchant_suzy00.html|title=Player Bio: Suzy Merchant|publisher=MSU Spartans}}</ref> During the 2007&ndash;2008 season, the team won more games, 23, than any other Big Ten team.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-04-17|url=http://msuspartans.cstv.com/sports/w-baskbl/spec-rel/wbaskbl-blog-main.html|title=MSU Women's Basketball |publisher=[[CBS College Sports Network]] }}</ref>

===Football===
{{main|Michigan State Spartans football|2008 Michigan State Spartans football team}}
[[American football|Football]] has a long tradition at Michigan State. Starting as a club sport in 1884, football gained varsity status in 1896.<ref>{{cite book | author=Grinczel, Steve. | title=They Are Spartans | location=Charleston, South Carolina | publisher=Arcadia Publishing | year=2003 | isbn= 0-7385-3214-2|pages=9}}</ref> Michigan State is often referred to the country's "football factory", especially during the 1950s when Detroit was the world's leading automobile manufacturer. During that time, the Spartans had a roster of impressive players, including Lynn Chandnois, Dorne Dibble, and Don McAulliffe. In 1951, the Spartans finished the season undefeated, and performed the same feat the following year in addition to the nation's longest winnig streak of 24 games. The team was named the "undisputed national champions by every official poll".<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.helmethut.com/College/MichState/MSU.html|title=Michigan State |publisher=Helmut Hut }}</ref>

After waiting for several years, the team was finally admitted into the Big 10 as a regular member in 1953. They promptly went on to capture the league championship (losing only one game during the season) and beating UCLA in their first Rose Bowl game. After the 1953 season [[Biggie Munn]], the legendary Spartan coach, turned the team over to his prot<U+00E9>g<U+00E9> and future legend [[Duffy Daugherty]].   He won the [[Rose Bowl Game|Rose Bowl]] in 1954 and 1956. George Perles was the head coach when the Spartans defeated USC in the Rose Bowl in January of 1988.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.stubhub.com/michigan-state-football-tickets/|title=Michigan State Spartans Football Tickets |publisher=[[StubHub]] }}</ref> All told, Michigan State has won or shared six national championships (1951, 1952, 1955, 1957, 1965 and 1966) and nine Big Ten championships.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://homepages.cae.wisc.edu/~dwilson/rfsc/history/kirlin/champs.html|title=Historical Reality National College Football Champions |publisher=[[University of Wisconsin-Madison]]|author=Kirlin, Bob }}</ref>

Today, the football team competes in [[Spartan Stadium, East Lansing|Spartan Stadium]], a renovated 75,005 person football stadium in the center of campus. The coach is [[Mark Dantonio]], who was hired on [[November 27]] [[2006]].<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-04-17|url=http://msuspartans.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/112706aaa.html|title=Mark Dantonio Named Michigan State's 24th Head Football Coach |publisher=[[CBS College Sports Network]]|date=2006-11-27 }}</ref> Dantonio had an 18&ndash;17 record in his three year tenure at the [[University of Cincinnati]], including a 1&ndash;0 Bowl Game record.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/news/story?id=2677122|title=Michigan State hires former Cincy coach Dantonio|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=2006-11-27}}</ref> Dantonio replaced [[John L. Smith]], who finished with a 22&ndash;26 record as the Spartans' head man.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/div_ia/bigten/michigan_state/coaching_records.php|title=Michigan State Coaching Records|publisher=College Football Data Warehouse}}</ref>

MSU's traditional archrival is the [[University of Michigan]], against whom they compete for the [[Paul Bunyan Trophy]]. MSU is traditionally the underdog, with a 28&ndash;66&ndash;5 record in the annual game.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/div_ia/bigten/michigan_state/opponents_records.php?teamid=1977|title=Michigan State vs. Michigan|publisher=College Football Data Warehouse}}</ref> Michigan State is one of three Big Ten teams to have an annual non-conference football game against [[University of Notre Dame|Notre Dame]]. MSU's record against the Fighting Irish is 25&ndash;44&ndash;1. One of the most [[1966 Notre Dame vs. Michigan State football game|memorable games in this series]] was in 1966 when the teams were ranked first (Notre Dame) and second (MSU) in the country.  The result of the game was a 10&ndash;10 tie when Notre Dame elected not to attempt a score when they had the ball late in the game.<ref>{{cite book|title=Biggest Game of Them All: Notre Dame, Michigan State and the Fall of 1966|author=Celizic, Mike |date=1992-11-01 |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |isbn=0671758179 |url=http://www.amazon.com/Biggest-Game-Them-All-Michigan/dp/0671758179/ }}</ref>

On the [[American Football League]]'s [[American Football League All-Time Team|All-Time Team]] are tight-end [[Fred Arbanas]]<ref name="fredarbansas">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/history/60s/|title=Chiefs History 1960s|publisher=[[Kansas City Chiefs]]}}</ref> and [[Safety (football position)|safety]] [[George Saimes]].<ref name="georgesaimes">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/S/SaimGe00.htm?redir|title=George Saimes Statistics|publisher=Pro Football Reference}}</ref> In the [[National Football League]], MSU alumni include [[Morten Andersen]],<ref name="mortenandersen">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.nflplayers.com/players/player.aspx?id=164|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20061125222400/http://www.nflplayers.com/players/player.aspx?id=164|archivedate=2006-11-25|title=Morten Andersen|publisher=NFLPlayers}}</ref> [[Plaxico Burress]],<ref name="plaxicoburress">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.nflplayers.com/players/player.aspx?id=28759|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20061125220147/http://www.nflplayers.com/players/player.aspx?id=28759|archivedate=2006-11-25|title=Plaxico Burress|publisher=NFLPlayers}}</ref> [[Andre Rison]],<ref name="andrerison">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://andrerison.com/index.html|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20070404165329/http://andrerison.com/index.html|archivedate=2007-04-04|title=Andre 'Bad Moon' Rison|publisher=AndreRison}}</ref> [[Derrick Mason]],<ref name="derrickmason">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.nflplayers.com/players/player.aspx?id=25021|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20061125214007/http://www.nflplayers.com/players/player.aspx?id=25021|archivedate=2006-11-25|title=Derek Mason|publisher=NFLPlayers}}</ref> [[Muhsin Muhammad]],<ref name="muhsinmuhammad">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.nflplayers.com/players/player.aspx?id=23866|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20061125201643/http://www.nflplayers.com/players/player.aspx?id=23866|archivedate=2006-11-25|title=Muhsin Muhammad|publisher=NFLPlayers}}</ref> [[T.J. Duckett]],<ref name="tjduckett">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.nflplayers.com/players/player.aspx?id=32994|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20061125222255/http://www.nflplayers.com/players/player.aspx?id=32994|archivedate=2006-11-25|title=T.J. Duckett|publisher=NFLPlayers}}</ref> [[Flozell Adams]],<ref name="flozelladams">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.nflplayers.com/players/player.aspx?id=25961|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20061125222536/http://www.nflplayers.com/players/player.aspx?id=25961|archivedate=2006-11-25|title=Flozell Adams|publisher=NFLPlayers}}</ref> [[Julian Peterson]],<ref name="julianpeterson">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.nflplayers.com/players/player.aspx?id=28767|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20061125200545/http://www.nflplayers.com/players/player.aspx?id=28767|archivedate=2006-11-25|title=Julian Peterson|publisher=NFLPlayers}}</ref> [[Charles Rogers]],<ref name="charlesrogers">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/R/RogeCh01.htm|title=Charles Rogers Statistics|publisher=Pro Football Reference}}</ref> [[Jim Miller (quarterback)|Jim Miller]],<ref name="jimmiller">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://msuspartans.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/050806aaa.html|title=MSU Announces Football Broadcast Team|publisher=MSU Spartans}}</ref> [[Earl Morrall]],<ref name="earlmorrall">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.mashf.com/1987_inductees.htm#Earl_Morrall|title=Class of '87|publisher=Muskegon Area Sports Hall of Fame}}</ref> [[Wayne Fontes]],<ref name="waynefontes">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/F/FontWa20.htm|title=Wayne Fontes Statistics|publisher=Pro Football Reference}}</ref> [[Bubba Smith]],<ref name="bubbasmith">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.collegefootball.org/famersearch.php?id=60009|title=George Webster|publisher=College Football Hall of Fame}}</ref> and [[Drew Stanton]].<ref name="drewstanton">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.sportsline.com/nfl/players/playerpage/421487|title=Drew Stanton|publisher=[[CBS Sports]]}}</ref> Former MSU quarterback [[Jeff Smoker]] now plays in the [[Arena Football League]].<ref name="jeffsmoker">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.azrattlers.com/team/roster/index.html?player_id=85|title=#15 Smoker, Jeff, QB|publisher=azrattlers}}</ref>

===Hockey===
[[Image:The Cold War UofM v.s MSU.jpg|thumb|right|300px|"The Cold War"]]
{{Main|Michigan State Spartans men's ice hockey}}
Michigan State has two varsity [[hockey]] teams: a men's [[ice hockey]] team and a women's [[field hockey]] team. Rolf van de Kerkhof is the head coach of the women's [[field hockey]] team. A native of [[Tilburg]], [[Netherlands]], van de Kerkhof's first win as head coach came on [[September 3]] [[2006]], with a 2&ndash;1 overtime victory against [[Temple University]].<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://msuspartans.cstv.com/sports/w-fieldh/mtt/vandekerkhof_rolf00.html|title=Player Bio: Rolf van de Kerkhof|publisher=MSU Spartans}}</ref>

The men's [[ice hockey]] team plays at the [[Munn Ice Arena]]. The head [[Coach (sport)|coach]] is [[Rick Comley]], who has a 116&ndash;73&ndash;19 record at MSU.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://msuspartans.cstv.com/sports/m-hockey/mtt/comley_rick00.html|publisher=MSU Spartans|title=Player Bio: Rick Comley}}</ref> Since the [[Big Ten Conference]] does not cover Division I [[ice hockey]], Michigan State competes in the [[Central Collegiate Hockey Association]]. Along with the [[University of Michigan]] (U-M) and the [[Ohio State University]], it is one of three [[Big Ten]] schools in the [[CCHA]].<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://msuspartans.cstv.com/sports/m-hockey/archive/msu-m-hockey-b4ccha.html|title=Michigan State Before Joining the CCHA |publisher=MSU Spartans }}</ref>

[[Image:Sparty Icehocky.jpg|thumb|200px|left|[[Sparty]] with a Hockey Jersey after Hockey team won the 2007 NCAA Men's Division I Tournament]] 
On [[October 6]], [[2001]], the team was involved in the most-attended [[ice hockey|hockey]] game in history: The Cold War. The Spartans set up a hockey rink in the middle of their football stadium, [[Spartan Stadium, East Lansing|Spartan Stadium]] and played U-M before a crowd of 74,554. The game ended in a 3&ndash;3 tie.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|publisher=MSU Spartans|url=http://msuspartans.cstv.com/sports/m-hockey/recaps/100601aaa.html|title= Spartan Hockey Ties Wolverines In Front Of Record Crowd|date=2001-10-06}}</ref>

The MSU ice hockey program has seven [[CCHA]] regular season championships and 11 [[CCHA Tournament]] titles.  MSU has also won 11 [[Great Lakes Invitational]] titles.  The Spartans have been in the NCAA tournament 23 times, with nine [[Frozen Four]] appearances and three national titles (1966, [[1986 NCAA Men's Division I Ice Hockey Tournament|1986]], and [[2007 NCAA Men's Division I Ice Hockey Tournament|2007]]). On [[April 7]] [[2007]] the Michigan State Spartans won their third Collegiate Championship by beating the [[Boston College Eagles]] 3&ndash;1.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://msuspartans.cstv.com/sports/m-hockey/recaps/040707aaa.html|title=Last-Minute Tally Hands Spartans Third NCAA Title Michigan State scores three times in the final period to beat Boston College 3-1|publisher=MSU Spartans|date=2007-04-07}}</ref>

Former Michigan State players in the [[National Hockey League]] include [[Rod Brind'Amour]],<ref name="rodbrindamour">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/pdisplay.php3?pid=576|title=Rod Brind'Amour|publisher=Internet Hockey Database}}</ref> [[Anson Carter]],<ref name="ansoncarter">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/pdisplay.php3?pid=847|title=Anson Carter|publisher=Internet Hockey Database}}</ref> [[Donald McSween]],<ref name="donaldmcsween">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/pdisplay.php3?pid=576|title=Don McSween|publisher=Internet Hockey Database}}</ref> [[Adam Hall]],<ref name="adamhall">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/pdisplay.php3?pid=44996|title=Adam Hall|publisher=Internet Hockey Database}}</ref> [[John-Michael Liles]], brothers [[Kelly Miller (hockey)|Kelly Miller]]<ref name="kellymiller">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/pdisplay.php3?pid%5B%5D=3728|title=Kelly Miller|publisher=Internet Hockey Database}}</ref> and [[Kip Miller]],<ref name="kipmiller">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/pdisplay.php3?pid=3730|title=Kip Miller|publisher=Internet Hockey Database}}</ref> as well as their cousins, brothers [[Ryan Miller (hockey player)|Ryan Miller]]<ref name="ryanmiller">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/pdisplay.php3?pid%5B%5D=45065|title=Ryan Miller|publisher=Internet Hockey Database}}</ref> and [[Drew Miller]].<ref name="drewmiller">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/pdisplay.php3?pid=69845|title=Drew Miller|publisher=Internet Hockey Database}}</ref> Two players for MSU have won the [[Hobey Baker Award]]: [[Kip Miller]] in 1990 and [[Ryan Miller (ice hockey)|Ryan Miller]] in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://msuspartans.cstv.com/sports/m-hockey/archive/msu-m-hockey-hobeybaker.html|title=Hobey Baker Memorial Award |publisher=MSU Spartans }}</ref>

===Other sports===
MSU has a number of other team sports. As in many other [[NCAA]] institutions, Michigan State has a [[college baseball|baseball]] team for men and a [[college softball|softball]] team for women. [[David Grewe]] is [[head coach]] of the MSU [[baseball]] team. Hired at age 29, Grewe is one of the youngest head coaches in the nation.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://msuspartans.cstv.com/sports/m-basebl/mtt/grewe_david00.html|title=Player Bio: David Grewe|publisher=MSU Spartans}}</ref> Former Michigan State players in [[Major League Baseball]] include [[Kirk Gibson]],<ref name="kirkgibson">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.baseball-almanac.com/players/player.php?p=gibsoki01|title=Kirk Gibson Baseball Stats|publisher=Baseball Almanac}}</ref> [[Steve Garvey]],<ref name="stevegarvey">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://spartanstars.home.comcast.net/~spartanstars/msubaseball.htm|title=Steve Garvey|publisher=Michigan State Baseball Alumni}}</ref> [[Robin Roberts (baseball player)|Robin Roberts]],<ref name="robinroberts">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.baseballhalloffame.org/hofers/index.jsp|title=Robin Roberts|publisher=National Baseball Hall of Fame}}</ref> and [[Mark Mulder]].<ref name="markmulder">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/team/player.jsp?player_id=150426|title=Mark Mulder|publisher=The Official Site of the St. Louis Cardinals}}</ref> The MSU women's fastpitch [[softball]] team won the [[Association for Intercollegiate Athletics for Women]] (AIAW) Division I national title in 1976. Its coach, Jacquie Joseph, has headed the program since 1994.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://msuspartans.cstv.com/sports/w-softbl/mtt/joseph_jacquie00.html|title=Player Bio: Jacquie Joseph|publisher=MSU Spartans}}</ref> Since taking over the program, Joseph has helped bring MSU to a record of 445&ndash;372&ndash;1 and four NCAA Regional appearances.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.jacquiejoseph.com/coach.html|title=The Coach|publisher=Jacquie Joseph}}</ref> The Spartan's also have a men's soccer team, which won two back-to-back championships in 1967 and 1968. They shared the 1968 title with the [[University of Maryland, College Park]].<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.ncaa.org/stats/m_soccer/ History|title=History - Past Champions|publisher=NCAA Men's Soccer}}</ref> The men's coach is Joe Baum, who is in his 31st year as head coach at Michigan State.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://msuspartans.cstv.com/sports/m-soccer/mtt/baum_joe00.html|title=Player Bio: Joe Baum|publisher=MSU Spartans}}</ref> Coaching the women's team is Baum's former assistant, Tom Saxton.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://msuspartans.cstv.com/sports/w-soccer/mtt/saxton_tom00.html|title=Player Bio: Tom Saxton|publisher=MSU Spartans}}</ref> There is also a volleyball team;  Cathy George has been the head coach of the women's [[volleyball]] team since 2005. During her first year at Michigan State, she led her team to a 12&ndash;18 record, including a 5&ndash;15, ninth-place finish in the conference standings.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://msuspartans.cstv.com/sports/w-volley/mtt/george_cathy00.html|title=Player Bio: Cathy George|publisher=MSU Spartans}}</ref>

There are a number of contact sports at MSU, including [[boxing]] and [[wrestling]]. MSU's [[boxing]] team won [[NCAA Boxing Championship|national titles]] in 1951 and 1955, although it is no longer an NCAA [[Varsity team|varsity]] sport.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.ncaa.org/library/records/winter_champs_records_book/2002/discontinued2.pdf|title=Discontinued Championships|publisher=Official 2002 NCAA Winter Championships Records Book}}</ref> Wrestling was one of the earliest sports formed at the [[Michigan Agricultural College]]. While the sport was dropped in 1906, it was reformed by the college 15 years later.<ref name="sports history">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.msu.edu/~msuarhc/sportshistory.ppt|publisher=MSU|title=Sports History}}</ref> The school's [[wrestling]] team has won the NCAA Division I championship once, in 1967.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.ncaa.com/history/default.aspx?id=88088|title=History - Past Champions|publisher=NCAA Men's Wrestling}}</ref> Its current coach, Tom Minkel, has produced 33 [[All-American]]s, 11 Big Ten Champions and one NCAA Champion.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://msuspartans.cstv.com/sports/m-wrestl/mtt/minkel_tom00.html|title=Player Bio: Tom Minkel|publisher=MSU Spartans}}</ref>

Water sports at MSU include rowing and swimming. MSU's women's [[rowing (sport)|rowing]] crew coach is Matt Weise. In his third year as MSU head coach, Weise coached the Spartans to a program-best sixth-place team finish at the [[NCAA Rowing Championships|NCAA Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://msuspartans.cstv.com/sports/w-crew/mtt/weise_matt00.html|title=Player Bio: Matt Weise|publisher=MSU Spartans}}</ref> Matt Gianiodis is the head coach of both the men and women's [[swimming]] and [[diving]]. In his four years as head coach, Spartan swimmers and divers have broken 14 varsity records.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://msuspartans.cstv.com/sports/c-swim/mtt/gianiodis_matt00.html|title=Player Bio: Matt Gianiodis|publisher=MSU Spartans}}</ref>

Other sports at MSU include [[cross country]], [[golf]], [[gymnastics]], and [[tennis]]. MSU's Men's cross country team won the [[NCAA]] Division I championship eight times from 1939 to 1959.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.ncaa.com/rankings/default.aspx?id=622|title=History - Past Champions|publisher=NCAA Men's & Women's Cross Country}}</ref> Walt Drenth is the current director of both the men's and women's cross country and [[track & field]] programs. After joining MSU in 2004, Drenth led men's cross country team to an NCAA Championship bid during the 2004 season. The women's cross country team also advanced to the NCAA Championship Meet after winning the Great Lakes Regional race.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://msuspartans.cstv.com/sports/c-xc/mtt/drenth_walt00.html|title=Player Bio: Walt Drenth|publisher=MSU Spartans}}</ref> 

Golf has had a long tradition at MSU. Hall of Fame Coach Bruce Fossum helped carry MSU to its first Big Ten title in 1969.<ref name="men's golf">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-04-17|url=http://msuspartans.cstv.com/sports/m-golf/spec-rel/040606aac.html|title=Men's Golf Set to Host 2006 Fossum Invitational|publisher=[[CBS College Sports Network]]|date=2006-04-06}}</ref> The Big Ten title would elude the Spartans until 2005, when arguably, the best team ever assembled, took home the rings in stellar fashion. Not only did the Spartans win the Big Ten Championship in 2005, but they captured two other titles along the way and rose all the way to #5 in the U.S. Sam Puryear coaches the men's [[golf]] team.<ref name="men's golf" /> A former assistant coach at [[Stanford University]], this is his first year as a head coach.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://msuspartans.cstv.com/sports/w-gym/mtt/klages_kathie00.html|title=Player Bio: Sam Puryear|publisher=MSU Spartans}}</ref> Stacy Slobodnik-Stoll coaches the women's team. In the last ten seasons, she has brought the Spartans to nine straight NCAA regional appearances.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://msuspartans.cstv.com/sports/w-golf/mtt/slobodnikstoll_stacy00.html|title=Player Bio: Stacy Slobodnik-Stoll|publisher=MSU Spartans}}</ref> 

The men's gymnastics team at MSU won one national title, which they shared with the [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign]] in 1958.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.ncaa.com/gymnastics-mens/default.aspx?id=264|title=History - Past Champions|publisher=NCAA Men's Gymnastics}}</ref> In 2001, the MSU [[Board of Trustees]] disbanded the team in order to comply with [[Title IX]] regulations.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://www.statenews.com/index.php/article/2001/04/gymnasts_don0146t_get|author=Dunlap, Keith|title=Gymnasts don<U+2019>t get their wish|publisher=[[The State News]]|date=2001-04-23}}</ref> The women's team retained its varsity status. Its coach is Kathie Klages, who has had 16 winning seasons in a row.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://msuspartans.cstv.com/sports/w-gym/mtt/klages_kathie00.html|title=Player Bio: Kathie Klages|publisher=MSU Spartans}}</ref> 

Gene Orlando is the coach of the men's tennis team. In his 17 years as MSU head coach, Orlando has taken the Spartan men to four NCAA Championship singles qualifiers.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://msuspartans.cstv.com/sports/m-tennis/mtt/orlando_gene00.html|title=Player Bio: Gene Orlando|publisher=MSU Spartans}}</ref> Coaching the women's team is Erica Perkins, a second-year head coach who, in her first year, led the Spartan women to a 12&ndash;11 record (2&ndash;8, [[Big Ten]].)<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-31|url=http://msuspartans.cstv.com/sports/w-tennis/mtt/perkins_erica00.html|title=Player Bio: Erica Perkins|publisher=MSU Spartans}}</ref>

